    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Blockages, like ice or even a particularly determined cluster of large, grumpy, flying insects—or perhaps a small, sticky piece of goblin chewing gum, if you're feeling imaginative—are the bane of any pitot tube's existence. When something obstructs the opening, it prevents the ram air from hitting the sensor properly, which immediately throws off the high-pressure reading.\n\nIf the tube is blocked, the pressure reading from the pitot tube drops, mimicking a condition of very low airspeed, even if the aircraft is flying at a brisk clip. The instrument will then show a dangerously low airspeed, potentially indicating a stall condition when you are perfectly fine. It's like trying to get a proper reading on a pressure gauge when a small, mischievous goblin has wedged a pebble right over the opening—the gauge is still there, but the input is completely corrupted.\n\nThe critical maintenance aspect is ensuring that the tube remains clear of any debris. You need to inspect it regularly, especially before flights in icing conditions, because a blockage can lead to a catastrophic failure of airspeed indication. If you rely on a faulty reading, you might fly into a situation where you are too slow, or worse, you might think you are too",
